22:18.560 --> 22:23.160
When Plato said quote nothing ever is but is always becoming and quote

22:23.160 --> 22:29.000
He delivered a text out of which we may derive something for he destroys by it not all practical

22:29.000 --> 22:35.740
But all speculative notions of cause and effect the whole series of things as they appear to us must be contemplated in time

22:35.740 --> 22:41.540
That is in succession and we conceive or suppose intervals between one state of things in another state of things

22:41.540 --> 22:46.960
So that there is priority in sequence and interval and being and is ceasing to be and beginning and ending

22:47.620 --> 22:51.100
But there is nothing of this kind in the nature of things

22:51.100 --> 22:53.740
It is an everlasting continuity

22:55.220 --> 23:01.780
When Antoninus speaks of generation he speaks of one cause acting and then another cause taking up the work

23:01.780 --> 23:09.260
Which the former left in a certain state and so on and we might conceive that he had some notion like what has been called quote

23:09.260 --> 23:16.500
the self-evolving power of nature and quote a fine phrase indeed the full import of which I believe that the writer of it did not see

23:16.500 --> 23:21.200
And thus he laid himself open to the imputation of being a follower of one of the Hindu sects

23:21.200 --> 23:27.480
Which makes all things come by evolution out of nature a matter or out of something which takes the place of the deity, but is not deity

23:28.820 --> 23:34.580
I would have all men think as they please or as they can and I only claim the same freedom which I give

23:35.080 --> 23:39.440
When a man writes anything we may fairly try to find out all that his words must mean

23:39.440 --> 23:44.200
Even if the result is that they mean what he did not mean and if we find this contradiction

23:44.200 --> 23:45.360
It is not our fault

23:45.360 --> 23:50.420
But his misfortune now Antoninus is perhaps somewhat in a condition in what he says though

23:50.420 --> 23:55.900
He speaks at the end of the paragraph of the power which acts unseen by the eyes, but still no less clearly

23:55.900 --> 24:02.960
But whether in this passage he means the power is conceived to be in different successive causes or in something else. Nobody can tell

24:02.960 --> 24:04.360
From other passages

24:04.360 --> 24:08.420
However, I do collect that his notion of the phenomena of the universe is what I have stated

24:08.420 --> 24:15.580
The deity works unseen if we may use such language and perhaps I may as job did or he wrote the book of job

24:15.580 --> 24:20.780
Quote in him we live and move and are end quote said saint paul to the athenians

24:20.780 --> 24:24.740
And to show his bearers that this was no new doctrine. He quoted the greek poets

24:24.740 --> 24:31.640
One of these poets was the stoic cleanthes whose noble hymn to zeus or god is an elevated expression of devotion and philosophy

24:31.640 --> 24:35.920
It deprives nature of her power and puts her under the immediate government of the deity

24:36.840 --> 24:37.320
quote

24:38.040 --> 24:44.480
The all this heaven which whirls around the earth obeys and willing follows where thou leadest without thee god

24:44.480 --> 24:51.500
Nothing is done on earth nor in the ethereal realms nor in the sea save what the wicked through their folly do end quote

24:51.500 --> 24:57.840
Antoninus conviction of the existence of a divine power and government was founded on his perception of the order of the universe

24:57.840 --> 25:04.520
Like socrates he says that though we cannot see the form of divine powers. We know that they exist because we see their works

25:05.720 --> 25:06.160
quote

25:06.760 --> 25:12.400
To those who asked where hast thou seen the gods or how dost thou comprehend that they exist and so worship with them?

25:12.500 --> 25:16.980
I answer in the first place that they may be seen even with the eyes in the second place

25:16.980 --> 25:20.040
Neither have I seen my own soul and yet I honor it

25:20.040 --> 25:24.260
Thus then with respect to the gods from what I constantly experience of their power from this

25:24.260 --> 25:27.800
I comprehend that they exist and I venerate them end quote

25:28.480 --> 25:33.740
This is a very old argument, which has always had great weight with most people and has appeared sufficient

25:34.580 --> 25:38.940
It does not acquire the least additional strength by being developed in the learned treatise

25:38.940 --> 25:42.880
It is as intelligible and its simple enunciation as it can be made

25:43.400 --> 25:46.580
If it is rejected, there is no arguing with him who rejects it

25:46.960 --> 25:54.040
And if it is worked out into innumerable particulars, the value of the evidence runs the risk of being buried under a mass of words

25:56.660 --> 26:02.820
Man being conscious that he has a spiritual power or intellectual power or that he has such a power in whatever way

26:02.820 --> 26:07.400
He conceives that he has it for I wish simply to state a fact from this power which he has in himself

26:07.400 --> 26:10.920
He has led as Antoninus says to believe that there is a greater power

26:10.920 --> 26:16.100
Which as the old stoics tell us pervades the whole universe as the intellect pervades man

26:16.940 --> 26:19.700
God exists then but what do we know of his nature?

26:21.100 --> 26:24.640
Antoninus says that the soul of man is an efflux from the divinity

26:24.640 --> 26:28.380
We have bodies like animals, but we have reason intelligence as the gods

26:29.720 --> 26:37.480
Animals have life and what we call instincts are natural principles of action, but the rational animal man alone has rational intelligence soul

26:38.140 --> 26:44.720
Antoninus insists on this continually god is in man and so he must constantly attend to the divinity within us

26:44.720 --> 26:48.140
For it is only in this way that we can have any knowledge of the nature of god

26:48.780 --> 26:55.760
The human soul is in a sense a portion of the divinity and the soul alone has any communication with the deity for as he says

26:55.760 --> 27:02.400
Quote with his intellectual part alone god touches the intelligence only which has flowed and has been derived from himself into these bodies

27:03.220 --> 27:06.960
End quote. In fact, he says that which is hidden within a man is life

27:06.960 --> 27:11.780
That is the man himself all the rest is vesture covering organs instrument

27:11.780 --> 27:15.920
Which the living man the real man uses for purposes of his present existence

27:15.920 --> 27:21.860
The air is universally diffused for him who is able to respire and so for him who is willing to partake of it

27:21.860 --> 27:27.080
The intelligent power which holds within it all things is diffused as wide and as free as the air

27:27.080 --> 27:31.300
It is by living a divine life that man approaches to a knowledge of the divinity

27:31.980 --> 27:34.500
It is by following the divinity within

27:34.500 --> 27:38.940
As Antoninus calls it that man comes nearest to the deity the supreme good

27:38.940 --> 27:42.840
For a man can never attain a perfect agreement with his internal guide

27:43.320 --> 27:44.760
Quote live with the gods

27:44.760 --> 27:51.280
And he does live with the gods who constantly shows them that his own soul is satisfied with that which is assigned to him

27:51.280 --> 27:57.800
And that it does all the demon wishes which sues hath given to every man for his guardian and guide a portion of himself

27:58.480 --> 28:02.660
And this demon is every man's understanding and reason end quote

28:03.580 --> 28:05.140
There is in man

28:05.140 --> 28:10.860
That is in the reason the intelligence a superior faculty which have exercised rules all the rest

28:10.860 --> 28:15.920
This is the ruling faculty which Cicero renders by the latin word principatus

28:15.920 --> 28:19.680
Quote to which nothing can or ought to be superior end quote

28:19.680 --> 28:26.720
Antoninus often uses this term in others which are equivalent he names it quote the governing intelligence end quote

28:27.680 --> 28:35.440
The governing faculty is the master of the soul a man must reverence only his ruling faculty and the divinity within him

28:35.440 --> 28:39.100
As we must reverence that which is supreme in the universe

28:39.100 --> 28:44.080
So we must reverence that which is supreme in ourselves and this is that which of the like kind

28:44.080 --> 28:46.540
With that which is the supreme in the universe

28:47.120 --> 28:47.680
So

28:48.300 --> 28:53.080
As platinus says the soul of man can only know the divine so far as it knows itself

28:53.660 --> 28:54.920
in one passage

28:54.920 --> 28:59.780
Antoninus speaks of a man's condemnation of himself when the diviner part within him has been

28:59.780 --> 29:05.140
Overpowered and yields to the less honorable and to the perishable part the body and its gross pleasures

29:06.060 --> 29:08.960
In a word the views of Antoninus on this matter

29:08.960 --> 29:16.520
However, his expressions may vary are exactly what bishop butler expresses when he speaks of quote the natural supremacy of the reflection or conscious

29:16.540 --> 29:24.280
End quote of the faculty quote which surveys approves or disapproves the several affectations of our mind and actions of our lives

29:24.280 --> 29:25.120
end quote

29:27.540 --> 29:32.140
Much matter might be collected from Antoninus on the notion of the universe being one animated being

29:32.140 --> 29:35.640
But all that he says amounts to no more is Schultz remarks than this

29:35.640 --> 29:41.560
The soul of man is most intimately united to his body and together they make one animal which we call man

29:41.560 --> 29:47.960
So the deity is most intimately united to the world or the material universe and together they form one whole

29:48.940 --> 29:55.200
But Antoninus did not view god in the material universe as the same any more than he viewed the body and soul of man as one

29:56.480 --> 29:59.520
Antoninus has no speculations on the absolute nature of the deity

29:59.520 --> 30:03.120
It was not his fashion to waste his time on what a man cannot understand

30:03.120 --> 30:09.660
He was satisfied that god exists that he governs all things that man can only have an imperfect knowledge of his nature

30:09.660 --> 30:15.940
And he must attain this imperfect knowledge by reverencing the divinity which is within him and keeping it pure

30:16.540 --> 30:23.300
From all that has been said it follows that the universe is administered by the providence of god and that all things are wisely ordered

30:23.300 --> 30:29.920
There are passages in which Antoninus expresses doubts or states different possible theories of the constitution and government of the universe

30:29.920 --> 30:34.640
But he always recurs to his fundamental principle that if we admit the existence of a deity

30:34.640 --> 30:38.000
We must also admit that he orders all things wisely and well

30:39.120 --> 30:43.700
Epictetus says that we can discern the providence which rules the world if we possess two things

30:43.700 --> 30:47.160
The power of seeing all that happens with respect to each thing

30:47.160 --> 30:49.060
and a grateful disposition

30:49.780 --> 30:52.000
But if all things are wisely ordered

30:52.000 --> 30:58.580
How is the world so full of what we call evil physical and moral if instead of saying that there is evil in the world

30:58.580 --> 31:05.140
We use the expression which I have used to quote what we call evil end quote. We have partly anticipated the emperor's answer

31:05.840 --> 31:10.300
We see and feel and know imperfectly very few things in the few years that we live

31:10.300 --> 31:16.540
And all the knowledge and all the experience of all the human race is positive ignorance of the whole which is infinite

31:17.200 --> 31:22.560
Now as our reason teaches us that everything is in some way related to and connected with every other thing

31:23.140 --> 31:26.720
All notion of evil as being in the universe of things is a contradiction

31:26.720 --> 31:30.120
For if the whole comes from and is covered by an intelligent being

31:30.120 --> 31:34.680
It is impossible to conceive anything in it which tends to the evil or destruction of the whole

31:36.120 --> 31:39.300
Everything is in constant mutation and yet the whole subsists

31:39.920 --> 31:44.380
We might imagine the solar system resolved into its elemental parts

31:44.380 --> 31:48.640
And yet the whole would still subsist quote ever young and perfect end quote

31:50.020 --> 31:57.060
All things all forms are dissolved and new forms appear all living things undergo the changes we call death

31:57.700 --> 32:00.720
If we call death an evil then all change is an evil

32:01.520 --> 32:09.520
Living beings also suffer pain and man suffers most of all for he suffers both in and by his body and by his intelligent part

32:10.080 --> 32:17.040
Men suffer also from one another and perhaps the largest part of human suffering comes to man from those whom he calls his brothers

32:18.980 --> 32:20.500
Antoninus says quote

32:20.500 --> 32:27.900
Generally wickedness does no harm at all to the universe and particularly the wickedness of one man does no harm to another

32:27.900 --> 32:33.720
It is only harmful to him who has it in his power to be released from it as soon as he shall choose end quote

32:35.140 --> 32:40.640
The first part of this is perfectly consistent with the doctrine that the whole can sustain no evil or harm

32:41.140 --> 32:47.100
The second part must be explained by the stoic principle that there is no evil in anything which is not in our power

32:47.100 --> 32:50.620
What wrong we suffer from another is his evil not ours

32:50.620 --> 32:53.520
But this is an admission that there is evil in a sort

32:53.520 --> 32:59.920
For he who does wrong does evil and if others can endure the wrong still there's evil in the wrongdoer

32:59.920 --> 33:05.220
Antoninus gives many excellent precepts with respect to wrongs and injuries and his precepts are practical

33:05.220 --> 33:11.240
He teaches us to bear what we cannot avoid and his lessons may be just as useful to him who denies the being and the government

33:11.240 --> 33:13.420
Is god as to him who believes in both?

33:14.020 --> 33:19.900
There is no direct answer in Antoninus to the objections which may be made to the existence and providence of god because of the moral

33:19.900 --> 33:26.060
Disorder and suffering which are in the world except this answer which he makes in reply to the supposition that even the best men

33:26.060 --> 33:27.700
May be extinguished by death

33:27.700 --> 33:34.580
He says if it is so we may be sure that if it ought to have been otherwise the gods would have ordered it otherwise

33:35.100 --> 33:39.620
His conviction of the wisdom which we may observe in the government of the world is too strong to be disturbed

33:39.620 --> 33:43.120
by any apparent irregularities in the order of things

33:43.680 --> 33:46.700
That these disorders exist is a fact

33:46.700 --> 33:51.160
And those would conclude from them against the being and government of god conclude too hastily

33:51.160 --> 33:57.360
We all admit that there is an order in the material world a nature in the sense in which the world has been explained

33:57.360 --> 34:03.080
A constitution what we call a system a relation of parts to one another and a fitness for the whole for something

34:03.580 --> 34:07.720
So in the constitution of plants and animals there is an order a fitness for some end

34:08.600 --> 34:13.300
Sometimes the order as we conceive it is interrupted and the end as we conceive it is not attained

34:13.300 --> 34:19.460
The seed the plant or the animal sometimes perishes before it is passed through all its changes and done all its uses

34:20.300 --> 34:21.800
It is according to nature

34:21.800 --> 34:28.000
That is a fixed order for some to perish early and for others to do all their uses and leave successors to take their place

34:28.000 --> 34:34.720
So man has a corporeal and intellectual and moral constitution fit for certain uses and on the whole man performs

34:34.720 --> 34:38.060
These uses dies and leaves other men in his place

34:38.060 --> 34:44.600
So society exists and a social state is manifestly the natural state of man the state for which his nature fits him

34:44.600 --> 34:49.200
And society amidst innumerable irregularities and disorders still subsists

34:49.200 --> 34:52.800
And perhaps we may say that the history of the past and our present knowledge

34:52.800 --> 34:58.860
Give us a reasonable hope that its disorders will diminish and that order its governing principle may be more firmly established

35:00.800 --> 35:07.820
As order then a fixed order we may say subject to deviations real or apparent must be admitted to exist in the whole of nature

35:07.820 --> 35:11.620
Of things that which we call disorder or evil as it seems to us

35:11.620 --> 35:16.760
Does not in any way alter the fact of the general constitution of things having a nature or fixed order

35:16.760 --> 35:21.040
Nobody will conclude from the existence of disorder that order is not the rule

35:21.040 --> 35:26.560
For the existence of order both physical and moral is proved by daily experience in all past experience

35:26.560 --> 35:29.880
We cannot conceive how the order of the universe is maintained

35:29.880 --> 35:36.140
We cannot even conceive how our own life from day to day is continued nor how we perform the simplest movements of the body

35:36.140 --> 35:41.420
Nor how we grow and think and act that we know many of the conditions which are necessary for all these functions

35:42.200 --> 35:46.460
Knowing nothing then the unseen power which acts in ourselves except by what is done

35:46.460 --> 35:50.520
We know nothing of the power which acts through what we call all time in all space

35:50.520 --> 35:54.640
But seeing that there is a nature or fixed order in all things known to us

35:54.640 --> 36:00.440
It is conformable to the nature of our minds to believe that this universal nature has a cause which operates continually

36:00.440 --> 36:05.560
And that we are totally unable to speculate on the reason of any of those disorders or evils which we perceive

36:06.400 --> 36:10.860
This I believe is the answer which may be collected from all that Antoninus has said

36:13.260 --> 36:15.900
The origin of evil is an old question

36:15.900 --> 36:18.860
Achilles tells Priam that Zeus has two casks

36:19.480 --> 36:22.260
One filled with good things and the other with bad

36:22.260 --> 36:29.760
And that he gives to men out of each according to his pleasure and so we must be content for we cannot alter the will of Zeus

36:30.320 --> 36:36.340
One of the greek commentators asked how we must reconcile this doctrine with what we find in the first book of the odyssey

36:37.220 --> 36:43.920
Where the king of the god says men say evil comes to them from us, but they bring it on themselves through their own folly

36:45.220 --> 36:48.400
The answer is plain enough even to the greek commentator

36:48.400 --> 36:52.640
The poets make both achilles and zeus speak appropriately to their several characters

36:52.640 --> 36:56.480
Indeed zeus says plainly that men do attribute their sufferings to the gods

36:56.480 --> 37:00.400
But they do it falsely for they are the cause of their own sorrows

37:03.320 --> 37:08.280
Epictetus and his encheridion make short work of the question of evil. He says quote

37:08.900 --> 37:15.400
As a mark is not set up for the purpose of missing it. So neither does the nature of evil exist in the universe end quote

37:16.420 --> 37:22.160
This will appear obscure enough to those who are not acquainted with epictetus, but he always knows what he is talking about

37:22.660 --> 37:26.100
We do not set up a mark in order to miss it though. We may miss it

37:26.580 --> 37:32.060
God whose existence epictetus assumes has not ordered all things so that his purpose shall fail

37:32.060 --> 37:36.960
Whatever there may be of what we call evil the nature of evil as he expresses it does not exist

37:36.960 --> 37:40.440
That is evil is not part of the constitution or nature of things

37:40.960 --> 37:47.600
If there were a principle of evil in the constitution of things evil would no longer be evil as simplicius argues

37:47.600 --> 37:49.500
But evil would be good

37:50.060 --> 37:55.920
Simplicius has a long and curious discourse on this text of epictetus and it is amusing and instructive

37:57.060 --> 37:59.160
One passage more will conclude this matter

37:59.160 --> 38:03.380
It contains all that the emperor could say quote to go from among men

38:03.380 --> 38:07.620
If there are gods, it's not a thing to be afraid of for the gods will not involve thee in evil

38:07.620 --> 38:11.500
But if indeed they do not exist or if they have no concern about human affairs

38:11.500 --> 38:15.140
What is it to me to live in a universe devoid of gods or devoid of providence?

38:15.780 --> 38:21.020
But in truth they do exist and they do care for human things and they have put all the mean in man's power to enable

38:21.020 --> 38:22.840
Him not to fall into real evils

38:22.840 --> 38:29.140
And as to the rest if there was anything evil they would have provided for this also that it should be altogether in a man's power

38:29.140 --> 38:30.560
not to fall into it

38:31.560 --> 38:33.760
But that which does not make a man worse

38:33.760 --> 38:35.880
How can it make a man's life worse?

38:36.240 --> 38:41.220
But neither through ignorance nor having the knowledge but not the power to guard against or correct these things

38:41.220 --> 38:44.540
Is it possible that the nature of the universe has overlooked them?

38:44.700 --> 38:50.060
Nor is it possible that it has made so great a mistake either if you want the power or want the skill that good and even

38:50.880 --> 38:52.700
Indiscriminately to the good and the bad

38:52.700 --> 38:59.640
But death certainly and life honor and dishonor pain and pleasure all these things equally happen to good and bad men

38:59.640 --> 39:05.220
Being things which make us neither better nor worse. Therefore. They are neither good nor evil

39:05.220 --> 39:06.340
end quote

39:07.520 --> 39:11.800
The ethical part of Antoninus's philosophy follows from his general principles

39:11.800 --> 39:18.660
The end of all his philosophy is to live conformably to nature both a man's own nature and the nature of the universe

39:19.700 --> 39:24.180
Bishop butler has explained what the greek philosophers meant when they spoke of living according to nature

39:24.180 --> 39:28.360
And he says that when it is explained as he has explained it and as they understood it

39:28.360 --> 39:34.640
It is quote a manner of speaking not loose and undetermined but clear and distinct strictly just and true

39:35.040 --> 39:35.720
end quote

39:36.700 --> 39:40.680
To live according to nature is to live according to a man's whole nature

39:40.680 --> 39:46.760
Not according to a part of it and to reverence the divinity within him as the governor of all his actions quote

39:46.760 --> 39:51.960
To the rational animal the same act is according to nature and according to reason end quote

39:52.500 --> 39:56.660
That which is done contrary to reason is also an act contrary to nature

39:56.660 --> 39:58.300
to the whole nature

39:58.300 --> 40:03.040
Though it is certainly conformable to some part of man's nature or it could not be done

40:03.040 --> 40:10.620
Man is made for action not for idleness or pleasure as plants and animals do the uses of their nature. So man must do his

40:11.260 --> 40:17.580
Man must also live conformably to the universal nature conformable to the nature of all things of which he is one and

40:17.580 --> 40:24.660
As a citizen of a political community, he must direct his life and actions with reference to those among whom and for whom

40:24.660 --> 40:26.820
Among other purposes he lives

40:27.800 --> 40:31.840
A man must not retire into solitude and cut himself off from his fellow men

40:31.840 --> 40:37.400
He must be ever active to do his part in the great whole all men are his kin not only in blood

40:37.400 --> 40:42.600
But still more by participating in the same intelligence and by being a portion of the same divinity

40:43.140 --> 40:47.820
A man cannot really be injured by his brethren for no act of theirs can make him bad

40:47.820 --> 40:50.320
And he must not be angry with them nor hate them

40:51.000 --> 40:51.480
quote

40:51.960 --> 40:57.740
For we are made for cooperation like feet like hands like eyelids like the rows of the upper and lower teeth

40:57.740 --> 41:00.860
To act against one another then is contrary to nature

41:00.860 --> 41:05.160
And it is acting against one another to be vexed and to turn away

41:05.160 --> 41:05.780
end quote

41:08.600 --> 41:15.660
Further he says quote take pleasure in one thing and rest in it in passing from one social act to another social act

41:15.660 --> 41:16.800
thinking of god

41:16.800 --> 41:18.400
end quote again

41:18.400 --> 41:19.700
quote love mankind

41:19.700 --> 41:21.740
Follow god end quote

41:22.360 --> 41:25.840
It is the characteristic of the rational soul for man to love his neighbor

41:26.840 --> 41:32.360
Antoninus teaches in various passages the forgiveness of injuries and we know that he also practiced what he taught

41:32.360 --> 41:38.200
Bishop butler remarks that quote this divine precept to forgive injuries and to love our enemies

41:38.200 --> 41:46.100
Though to be met with genteel moralist yet is in a particular sense a precept of christianity as our savior has insisted more upon it

41:46.100 --> 41:48.660
Than on any other single virtue end quote

41:50.080 --> 41:53.720
The practice of this precept is the most difficult of all virtues

41:53.720 --> 41:58.400
Antoninus often enforces it and gives us aid towards following it when we are injured

41:58.400 --> 42:03.580
We feel anger and resentment and the feeling is natural just and useful for the conservation of society

42:03.580 --> 42:10.180
It is useful that wrongdoers should feel the natural consequences of their actions among which is the disapprobation of society

42:10.180 --> 42:12.160
And the resentment of him who is wronged

42:12.780 --> 42:16.400
But revenge in the proper sense of that word must not be practiced

42:17.260 --> 42:24.300
Quote the best way of avenging thyself end quote says the emperor quote is not to become like the wrongdoer end quote

42:24.900 --> 42:28.940
It is plain by this that he does not mean that we should in any case practice revenge

42:28.940 --> 42:33.960
But he says to those who talk of revenging wrongs be not like him who has done the wrong

42:33.960 --> 42:39.640
Socrates in the credo says the same in other words in saint paul quote when a man has done the any wrong

42:39.640 --> 42:43.540
Immediately consider with what opinion about good or evil he has done wrong

42:43.540 --> 42:49.160
For when that has seen this that will pity him and won't neither wonder nor be angry end quote

42:50.520 --> 42:56.860
Antoninus would not deny that wrong naturally produces the feeling of anger and resentment for this is implied in the recommendation to reflect

42:56.860 --> 43:01.780
On the nature of the man's mind who has done the wrong and then you will have pity instead of resentment

43:01.780 --> 43:07.720
And so it comes to the same as saint paul's advice to be angry and sin not which as butler well explains it

43:07.720 --> 43:12.020
It's not a recommendation to be angry which nobody needs for anger is a natural passion

43:12.020 --> 43:15.540
But it is a warning against allowing anger to lead us into sin

43:16.180 --> 43:19.980
In short the emperor's doctrine about wrongful acts is this

43:21.240 --> 43:27.820
Wrongdoers do not know what good and bad are they offend out of ignorance and in the sense of the stoics. This is true

43:28.980 --> 43:35.140
Though this kind of ignorance will never be admitted as a legal excuse and ought not to be admitted as a full excuse in any way

43:35.140 --> 43:41.420
By society there may be grievous injuries such as it is in a man's power to forgive without harm to society

43:41.940 --> 43:45.520
And if he forgives because he sees that his enemies know not what they do

43:45.540 --> 43:52.500
He is acting in the spirit of the sublime prayer quote father forgive them for they know not what they do end quote

43:54.400 --> 43:57.640
The emperor's moral philosophy was not a feeble narrow system

43:57.640 --> 44:05.080
Which teaches man to look directly to his own happiness though a man's happiness or tranquility is indirectly promoted by living as he ought to do

44:05.080 --> 44:08.080
A man must live conformably to the universal nature

44:08.080 --> 44:14.080
Which means as the emperor explains it in many passages that a man's action must be conformable to his true

44:14.080 --> 44:20.400
Relations to all other human beings both as a citizen of a political community and as a member of the whole human family

44:20.400 --> 44:27.120
This implies and he often expresses it in the most forcible language that a man's words and actions so far as they affect others

44:27.120 --> 44:28.700
Must be measured by a fixed rule

44:28.700 --> 44:36.420
Which is their consistency with the conservation and the interests of the particular society of which he is a member and of the whole human race

44:37.060 --> 44:38.880
To live conformably to such a rule

44:38.880 --> 44:46.440
A man must use his rational faculties in order to discern clearly the consequences and full effect of all his actions and of the actions of others

44:46.980 --> 44:50.200
He must not live a life of contemplation and reflection only though

44:50.200 --> 44:55.520
He must often retire within himself to calm and purify his soul by thought but he must mingle in the work of man

44:55.520 --> 44:57.920
And be a fellow laborer for the general good

44:59.540 --> 45:05.800
A man should have an object or purpose in life that he may direct all his energies to it, of course a good object

45:05.800 --> 45:11.020
He who is not one object or purpose of life cannot be one in the same all through his life

45:11.020 --> 45:17.420
Bacon has a remark to the same effect on the best means of quote reducing of the mind unto virtue and good estate

45:17.420 --> 45:22.640
Which is the electing and propounding unto a man's self-good and virtuous ends of his life

45:22.640 --> 45:27.120
Such as may be in a reasonable sort within his compass to attain end quote

45:29.220 --> 45:34.520
He is a happy man who has been wise enough to do this when he was young and has had the opportunities

45:34.520 --> 45:39.100
But the emperor seeing well that a man cannot always be so wise in his youth

45:39.100 --> 45:44.700
Encourages him to do it when he can and not to let his life slip away before he has begun

45:45.340 --> 45:52.560
He who can propose to himself good and virtuous ends of life and be true to them cannot fail to live conformably to his own interest

45:52.560 --> 45:56.080
And universal interest for in the nature of things they are one

45:56.600 --> 46:00.760
If a thing is not good for the hive, it is not good for the bee

46:01.800 --> 46:03.940
One passage may end this matter

46:03.940 --> 46:08.580
Quote if the gods have determined about me and about the things which must happen to me

46:08.580 --> 46:13.220
They have determined well for it is not easy even to imagine a deity without forethought

46:13.860 --> 46:15.280
And as to doing me harm

46:15.280 --> 46:20.720
Why should they have any desire towards that for what advantage would result to them for this or to the whole?

46:21.240 --> 46:23.360
Which is the special object of their providence

46:23.360 --> 46:29.020
But if they have not determined about me individually they have certainly determined about the whole at least

46:29.020 --> 46:35.540
And the things which happen by way of sequence in this general arrangement I ought to accept with pleasure and to be content with them

46:36.780 --> 46:38.760
But if they determine about nothing

46:38.760 --> 46:44.800
Which it is wicked to believe or if we do believe it let us neither sacrifice nor pray nor swear by them nor do anything else

46:44.800 --> 46:47.180
Which we do as if the gods were present and lived with us

46:47.180 --> 46:52.240
But if however the gods determine about none of these things which concern us I am able to determine about myself

46:52.240 --> 46:56.220
And I can inquire about that which is useful and that is useful to every man

46:56.220 --> 46:59.080
Which is conformable to his own constitution and nature

46:59.900 --> 47:05.680
But my nature is rational and social and my city and country so far as I am Antoninus is Rome

47:06.280 --> 47:09.500
But so far as I am a man it is the world

47:09.500 --> 47:14.200
The things then which are useful to these cities are alone useful to me

47:16.540 --> 47:22.760
It would be tedious and it is not necessary to state that the emperor's opinions on all the ways in which a man may profitably use

47:22.760 --> 47:28.780
His understanding towards perfecting himself in practical virtue the passages to this purpose are in all parts of his book

47:28.780 --> 47:34.500
But as they are in no order or connection a man must use the book a long time before he will find out all that is in it

47:35.000 --> 47:36.860
A few words may be added here

47:36.860 --> 47:43.620
If we analyze all other things we find how insufficient they are for human life and how truly worthless many of them are

47:44.440 --> 47:47.820
Virtue alone is indivisible one and perfectly satisfying

47:48.540 --> 47:51.880
The notion of virtue cannot be considered vague or unsettled

47:51.880 --> 47:57.940
Because a man may find it difficult to explain the notion fully to himself or to expound it to others in such a way to prevent

47:57.940 --> 48:03.400
Conveiling virtue is a whole and no more consists of parts than man's intelligence does and yet

48:03.400 --> 48:07.800
We speak of various intellectual faculties as convenient way of expressing the various powers

48:07.800 --> 48:11.400
Which man's intellect shows by his works in the same way

48:11.400 --> 48:15.160
We may speak of various virtues or parts of virtue in a practical sense

48:15.160 --> 48:20.900
For the purpose of showing what particular virtues we ought to practice in order to exercise of the whole of virtue

48:20.900 --> 48:24.460
That is as much as man's nature is capable of

48:26.200 --> 48:29.280
The prime principle in man's constitution is social

48:29.280 --> 48:35.160
The next in orders is not to yield to the persuasions of the body when they are not conformable to the rational principle

48:35.160 --> 48:39.980
Which must govern the third is freedom from error and from deception quote

48:40.580 --> 48:44.380
Let then the ruling principle holding fast to these things go straight on

48:44.380 --> 48:47.340
And it has what is its own end quote

48:47.340 --> 48:54.560
The emperor selects justice as the virtue which is the basis of all the rest and this had been said long before his time

48:56.120 --> 49:01.400
It is true that all people have some notion of what is meant by justice as a disposition of the mind

49:01.400 --> 49:04.800
And some notion about acting and conformity to this disposition

49:05.920 --> 49:13.020
But experience shows that men's notions about justice are as confused as their actions are inconsistent with the true notion of justice

49:13.660 --> 49:19.760
The emperor's notion of justice is clear enough, but not practical enough for all mankind quote

49:19.760 --> 49:24.560
Let there be freedom from perturbations with respect to the things which come from the external cause

49:24.560 --> 49:28.120
And let there be justice in the things done by virtue of the internal cause

49:28.120 --> 49:35.340
That is let there be a movement and action terminating in this and social acts for this is according to thy nature

49:35.340 --> 49:38.400
End quote in another place. He says that quote

49:38.400 --> 49:42.460
He who acts unjustly acts impiously end quote

49:43.020 --> 49:45.880
Which follows of course from all that he says in various places

49:46.600 --> 49:50.680
He insists on the practice of truth as a virtue and as a means to virtue

49:50.680 --> 49:56.800
Which it no doubt is for lying even in indifferent things weakens the understanding and lying maliciously

49:56.800 --> 50:04.060
Is as great a moral offense as man can be guilty of viewed both as showing an habitual disposition and viewed with respect to consequences

50:04.680 --> 50:07.180
He couples the notion of justice with action

50:07.180 --> 50:13.640
A man must not pride himself on having some fine notion of justice in his head, but he must exhibit his just in an act

50:13.640 --> 50:15.900
Like saint james notion of faith

50:16.460 --> 50:17.940
But this is enough

50:19.280 --> 50:24.220
The stoics and Antoninus among them call some things beautiful and some ugly

50:24.220 --> 50:29.540
And as they are beautiful, so they are good and as they are ugly so they are evil or bad

50:30.060 --> 50:33.060
All these things good and evil are in our power. Absolutely

50:33.660 --> 50:39.840
Some of the stricter stoics would say in a manner only as those who would not depart altogether from common sense would say

50:39.840 --> 50:44.080
Practically they are to a great degree in the power of some persons and in some circumstances

50:44.080 --> 50:48.140
But in a small degree only in other persons and in other circumstances

50:49.180 --> 50:55.320
The stoics maintain man's free will as to the things which are in his power for as to the things which are out of his power

50:55.320 --> 50:59.660
Free will terminating inaction is of course excluded by the very terms of the expression

51:00.200 --> 51:04.760
I hardly know if we can discover exactly Antoninus notion of the free will of man

51:04.760 --> 51:07.060
Nor is the question worth the inquiry

51:07.820 --> 51:10.560
What he does mean and does say is intelligible

51:10.560 --> 51:16.860
All the things which are not in our power are indifferent. They are neither good nor bad morally

51:16.860 --> 51:20.520
Such are life health wealth power disease poverty and death

51:21.260 --> 51:29.040
Life and death are all men's portion health wealth power disease and poverty happen to men indifferently to the good and to the bad

51:29.040 --> 51:32.380
To those who live according to nature and to those who do not

51:33.320 --> 51:34.440
quote life

51:34.440 --> 51:40.240
Says the emperor is a warfare and a stranger's children and after fame is oblivion end quote

51:41.760 --> 51:48.340
After speaking of those men who have disturbed the world and then died and of the death of philosophers such as heraclitus and democratus

51:48.340 --> 51:51.040
Who was destroyed by lice and of socrates?

51:51.040 --> 51:58.060
Whom other lice his enemies destroyed he says quote what means all this thou has embarked thou has made the voyage

51:58.060 --> 52:04.080
Thou art come to shore get out if indeed to another life. There is no want of gods not even there

52:04.580 --> 52:09.140
But if to a state without sensation that will cease to be held by pains and pleasures

52:09.140 --> 52:13.840
And to be a slave to the vessel which is as much inferior to that which serves it as superior

52:13.840 --> 52:18.740
For the one is intelligence and deity the other is earth and corruption end quote

52:19.320 --> 52:24.220
It is not death that man should fear, but he should fear never beginning to live according to his nature

52:25.160 --> 52:30.540
Every man should live in such a way as to discharge his duty and to trouble himself about nothing else

52:30.540 --> 52:36.780
He should live such a life that he shall always be ready for death and shall depart content when the summon comes

52:36.780 --> 52:38.940
for what is death quote

52:38.940 --> 52:45.860
a cessation of the impressions through the senses and of the pulling of the strings which move the appetites and of the

52:45.860 --> 52:49.380
discursive movements of the thoughts and of the service to the flesh

52:49.940 --> 52:54.420
End quote death is such as generation is a mystery of nature

52:55.740 --> 52:59.460
In another passage the exact meaning of which is perhaps doubtful

52:59.460 --> 53:04.240
He speaks of the child which leaves the womb and so he says the soul at death leaves its envelope

53:04.740 --> 53:07.800
As the child is born or comes into life by leaving the womb

53:08.420 --> 53:12.620
So the soul may on leaving the body pass into another existence, which is perfect

53:13.780 --> 53:15.940
I'm, not sure if this is the emperor's meaning

53:17.460 --> 53:20.460
Antoninus's opinion of a future life is nowhere clearly expressed

53:21.100 --> 53:28.020
His doctrine of the nature of the soul of necessity implies that it does not perish absolutely for a portion of divinity cannot perish

53:28.580 --> 53:32.540
The opinion is at least as old as the time of epicharmus and europides

53:32.540 --> 53:38.480
What comes from the earth goes back to the earth and what comes from heaven the divinity returns to him who gave it

53:39.420 --> 53:43.840
But I find nothing clear in Antoninus as to the notion of the man existing after death

53:43.840 --> 53:48.200
So as to be conscious of his sameness with the soul which occupied his vessel of clay

53:49.240 --> 53:53.680
He seemed to be perplexed on this matter and finally to have rested in this

53:53.680 --> 53:58.360
That god or the gods will do whatever is best and consistent with the university of things

54:00.840 --> 54:06.180
Nor I think does he speak conclusively on another stoic doctrine which some stoics practice

54:06.180 --> 54:10.160
The anticipating the regular course of nature by man's own act

54:11.460 --> 54:16.700
The reader will find some passages in which this is touched on and he may make of them what he can

54:16.700 --> 54:22.620
But there are passages in which the emperor encourages himself to wait for the end patiently and with tranquility

54:22.620 --> 54:30.300
And certainly it is consistent with all his best teaching that a man should bear all that falls to his lot and do useful acts as long as he lives

54:31.040 --> 54:35.360
He should not therefore abridge the time of his usefulness by his own act

54:36.000 --> 54:40.140
Whether he contemplates any possible cases in which a man should die by his own hand

54:40.140 --> 54:46.460
I cannot tell and the matter is not worth the curious inquiry for I believe it would not lead to any certain result

54:46.460 --> 54:48.060
As to his opinion on this point

54:49.260 --> 54:53.020
I do not think that Antoninus who never mentioned Seneca though

54:53.020 --> 54:57.800
He must have known all about him would have agreed with Seneca when he gives us a reason for suicide

54:57.800 --> 55:01.840
That the eternal law whatever he means has made nothing better for us than this

55:01.840 --> 55:06.240
That it has given us only one way of entering life and many ways of going out of it

55:07.240 --> 55:12.620
The ways of going out indeed are many and that is a good reason for a man taking care of himself

55:13.740 --> 55:16.660
Happiness was not the direct object of a stoic's life

55:17.420 --> 55:21.760
There is no rule of life contained in the precept that a man should pursue his own happiness

55:22.940 --> 55:30.300
Many men think that they are seeking happiness when they are only seeking the gratification of some particular passion the strongest that they have

55:31.260 --> 55:35.640
The end of a man is as already explained to live conformably to nature

55:35.640 --> 55:39.020
And he will thus obtain happiness tranquility of mind and contentment

55:40.100 --> 55:46.520
As a means of living conformably to nature he must study the four chief virtues each of which has its proper sphere

55:47.460 --> 55:49.980
wisdom or the knowledge of good and evil

55:49.980 --> 55:52.920
Justice or the giving to every man has due

55:54.200 --> 56:00.300
Fortitude or the enduring of labor and pain and temperance which is moderation in all things

56:01.160 --> 56:05.560
By thus living conformably to nature the stoic obtained all that he wished or expected

56:05.640 --> 56:10.180
His reward was in his virtuous life and he was satisfied with that

56:11.100 --> 56:13.400
Some greek poet long ago wrote

56:14.020 --> 56:14.660
quote

56:15.240 --> 56:20.120
For virtue only of all human things takes reward not from the hands of others

56:20.120 --> 56:23.440
Virtue herself rewards the toils of virtue

56:23.440 --> 56:24.880
end quote

56:26.280 --> 56:32.920
Some of the stoics indeed express themselves in very arrogant absurd terms about the wise man's self-sufficiency

56:33.480 --> 56:35.460
They elevated him to the rank of a deity

56:36.200 --> 56:44.280
These were only talkers and lecturers such as those in all ages who utter fine words knowing little of human affairs and caring only for notoriety

56:46.020 --> 56:51.220
Epictetus and Antoninus both by precept and example labor to improve themselves and others

56:51.800 --> 56:54.320
And if we discover imperfections in their teaching

56:54.320 --> 56:58.980
We must still honor these great men who attempted to show that there is in a man's nature

56:58.980 --> 57:03.060
And in the constitution of things sufficient reason for living a virtuous life

57:04.180 --> 57:11.100
It is difficult enough to live as we ought to live difficult even for any man to live in such a way as to satisfy himself

57:11.100 --> 57:17.300
If he exercises only in a moderate degree the power of reflecting upon and reviewing his own conduct

57:18.060 --> 57:22.040
And if all men cannot be brought to the same opinions and morals and religion

57:22.040 --> 57:27.660
It is at least worthwhile to give them good reasons for as much as they can be persuaded to accept

57:29.420 --> 57:30.340
And

57:30.980 --> 57:35.280
Meditations of Marcus Aurelius Antoninus section 14

57:36.360 --> 57:39.040
The philosophy of Antoninus by george long

57:40.040 --> 57:43.860
End of meditations of Marcus Aurelius

58:01.920 --> 58:03.320
You

